These questions assume that your mother died leaving a will and also
an estate and, if so, that whoever she named as executor or other
fiduciary at the time and others then interested in her estate acted
in accordance with what her will directed.

Also - at least unless explained further with more facts about your
and your mother's relationship and about her estate - your apparent
assumption that you had to be or even that you should have been
"fairly included" is likely to be at best meaningless if you relatedly
believe that there is some sort of obligation generally imposed by law
that a parent "include" a child in the sense of providing in his or
her will or functionally equivalent other estate disposing of
instrument some benefit for a child.

If a deceased did die leaving a will, the usually least inefficient
way to get a copy is to ask the persons who based on the facts one
knows about the deceased most probably have one - e.g., surviving
children and other family members, close friends, the deceased's
estate's lawyer, etc.

Failing this, if there was a will probated in Calif. in other than
"small estate" manner, a copy would be findable in the branch of the
superior court in the county in which the deceased had been
permanently residing at the time of death and, even if "small estate"
procedures were used, the facts about the will often are similarly
findable.

Bear in mind, too, however, that perhaps comparatively more so than
residents of other states which don't have similar laws encouraging
this, many Calif. residents who believe they will die leaving an
estate opt for the comparatively unique Calif. version of trusts (
including what compared with generally prevailing law in most other
jurisdictions are oxymoronically referred to as "self trusteed" ones),
which, if done carefully/efficiently and otherwise properly, do not
require filing in any court.

The way to assess the extent if at all to which one has been provided
for in a will and whether a will was properly executed is to read it.

Given your "several years back" comment, note, too, that are important
differences both of substance and of timing - in particular, whether
and, if so, when it will have become too late to make a claim to all
or a portion of a deceased's estate - between a person named
individually as a beneficiary or because he or she is a member of some
identified class of beneficiaries named in a will who is not given a
copy of the will by whoever is administering the estate and someone -
even if a child of the deceased - not provided for by (perhaps because
simply omitted from mention in) a will.
