<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;My mom died several years back, and at the time I was so upset that I
&gt;didn't get too involved.  Now that the dust has settled and there's
&gt;some distance from the event, several questions have emerged in my
&gt;mind.

&gt;1.) I never got a copy of the will.  She was a California resident.
&gt;How can I get a copy of the will?
">

Have you considered asking the executor?  Do you know who that is?
Your father?  Your mother's bank's trust department?

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;2.) Once I get a copy of the will, how can I assess whether it was
&gt;properly executed and be certain I was fairly included?
">

First, read it.  Maybe you need the advise of a lawyer here, but
first just read it yourself.  If you were supposed to get a fixed
amount or fixed list of items, did you get those?  Assuming you are
included at all, you have the right to ask for an accounting of the
division of the estate.  For example, if you're supposed to get
one-third of the whole estate, it might end up that A gets the car
and some of the furniture, B gets the house, and C gets the vacation
home, and all of them get some part of the cash left in the estate
(A perhaps getting more as the car and furniture is not worth as
much as the houses).

If it's a fair division, the executor should be able to demonstrate
that reasonable valuations of things like the car, furniture, and
houses give A, B, and C about equal totals.
